Wood and their BTU. 

One of the many reasons we engage in winter tree, identification is to find more efficient wood for the task at hand.  This weekend I will be burning a large amount of old Barn wood that is discarded and not much use anywhere else. I’m going to utilize cedar as tinder to get it going. Cedar has a lot of oils that make its flashpoint lower to help get a fire started, especially in rainy conditions Everything is mostly soaking wet except the cedar that I have split to get started. I have split up some oak to utilize on top of the cedar. The oak will add higher BTU so the rain soaked barn material can burn.  Work smarter not harder.
This is why I cannot workout at Planet Fitness.  Too much grunting and tossing of weights.  Still going, better than I was yesterday.  #behardtokill

3 Rs of wilderness education.  Retain, relate, recall.  Can the people listening to a teacher retain the info being taught? As an instructor find a way to make it relatable so there is connection to the content.  Important for survival (in this class I was teaching Lost Proofing) is to make the info useful so it can be be recalled under stress.

Is @naturereliance’s Essential Wilderness Navigation the best introductory land navigation book on the market?? I’d say so.
•
Chock full of stories, illustrations, practice questions (with an answer key) and field exercises…. not to mention a FULL SIZE MAP stuck under the back cover for the table top exercises… 🤯
•
Whether you are brand new to land nav or a land nav nerd, check this one it out! These are available on Amazon and any major book retailer. Grab one, get up to speed and then if you want to take it up a notch, get yourself in a Nature Reliance School land navigation class! Like Craig says, “come on, join in, let’s learn together!”
